# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 3d-lookup-table
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] In the film and graphics industries, **3D lookup tables** (**3D LUT**s) are used for color grading and for mapping one color space to another.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] They are commonly used to calculate preview colors for a monitor or digital projector of how an image will be reproduced on another display device, typically the final digitally projected image or release print of a movie.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] A 3D LUT is a 3D lattice of output RGB color values that can be indexed by sets of input RGB colour values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Each axis of the lattice represents one of the three input color components; the input color thus defines a point inside the lattice.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Since the point may not be on a lattice point, the lattice values must be interpolated; most products use trilinear interpolation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] 3D LUTs are used extensively in the movie production chain, as part of the digital intermediate process.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Cubes may be of various sizes and bit depths.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Often 33×33×33 cubes are used as 3D LUTs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] The most common practice is to use RGB 10-bit/component log images as the input to the 3D LUT.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Output is usually RGB values that are to be placed unchanged into a display device's buffer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Modern GPU of graphics cards have direct support for 3D LUTs, allowing entire HD images to be processed at 60 fps or faster.
[src:3d-lookup-table/3d-lookup-table] Also, modern display controller of monitors have support for 3D LUTs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The aim of **color calibration** is to measure and/or adjust the color response of a device (input or output) to a known state.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] In International Color Consortium (ICC) terms, this is the basis for an additional color characterization of the device and later profiling.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] In non-ICC workflows, calibration sometimes refers to establishing a known relationship to a standard color space in one go.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The device that is to be calibrated is sometimes known as a *calibration source*; the color space that serves as a standard is sometimes known as a *calibration target*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Color calibration is a requirement for all devices taking an active part in a color-managed workflow and is used by many industries, such as television production, gaming, photography, engineering, chemistry, medicine, and more.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Input data can come from device sources like digital cameras, image scanners, or any other measuring devices.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Input data is, in most cases, calibrated against a profile connection space (PCS).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] One of the most important factors to consider when dealing with color calibration is having a valid source.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] If the color measuring source does not match the display's capabilities, the calibration will be ineffective and give false readings.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] After this, the data is often circulated in the system and translated into a working space RGB for viewing and editing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] In the output stage, when exporting to a viewing device such as a cathode ray tube, liquid crystal display screen, or digital projector, the computer sends a signal to the computer's graphic card in the form of RGB [Red, Green, Blue].
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The dataset [255,0,0] signals only a device instruction, not a specific color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] This instruction [R,G,B]=[255,0,0] then causes the connected display to show Red at the maximum achievable brightness [255], while the Green and Blue components of the display remain dark [0].
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Hence, every output device will have its own unique color signature, displaying a certain color according to manufacturing tolerances and material deterioration through use and age.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] If the output device is a printer, additional distorting factors are the qualities of a particular batch of paper and ink.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The conductive qualities and standards-compliance of connecting cables, circuitry, and equipment can also alter the electrical signal at any stage in the signal flow.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Color perception is subject to ambient light levels, and the ambient white point; for example, a red object looks black in blue light.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] It is therefore not possible to achieve calibration that will make a device look correct and consistent in all capture or viewing conditions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The computer display and calibration target will have to be considered in controlled, predefined lighting conditions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The most common form of calibration aims at adjusting cameras, scanners, monitors, and printers for photographic reproduction.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The aim is that a printed copy of a photograph appears identical in saturation and dynamic range to the original or a source file on a computer display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] These goals can either be realized via direct value translation from source to target, or by using a common known reference color space as middle ground.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] In the most commonly used color profile system, ICC, this is known as the PCS or "Profile Connection Space".
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The camera calibration needs a known calibration target to be photographed and the resulting output from the camera to be converted to color values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] A correction profile can then be built using the difference between the camera result values and the known reference values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] When two or more cameras need to be calibrated relatively to each other, to reproduce the same color values, the technique of color mapping can be used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] For creating a scanner profile it needs a target source, such as an IT8-target, an original with many small color fields, which was measured by the developer with a photometer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The scanner reads this original and compares the scanned color values with the target's reference values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Taking the differences of these values into account an ICC profile is created, which relates the device-specific color space (RGB color space) to a device-independent color space (L*a*b* color space).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Thus, the scanner is able to output with color fidelity to what it reads.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] For calibrating the monitor a colorimeter is attached flat to the display's surface, shielded from all ambient light.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The calibration software sends a series of color signals to the display and compares the values that were actually sent against the readings from the calibration device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] This establishes the current offsets in color display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Depending on the calibration software and type of monitor used, the software either creates a correction matrix (i.e. an ICC profile) for color values before being sent to the display or gives instructions for altering the display's brightness/contrast and RGB values through the OSD.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] This tunes the display to reproduce fairly accurately the in-gamut part of a desired color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The calibration target for this kind of calibration is that of print stock paper illuminated by D65 light at 120 cd/m2.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The color calibration for display devices is usually aim for certain color spaces, such as sRGB and/or DCI-P3.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] An example of the famous cross-platform display calibration software is **DisplayCAL**.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The ICC profile for a printer is created by comparing a test print result using a photometer with the original reference file.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] The test chart contains known CMYK colors, whose offsets to their actual L*a*b* colors scanned by the photometer result in an ICC profile.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] Another possibility to ICC profile a printer is to use a calibrated scanner as the measuring device for the printed CMYK test chart instead of a photometer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-calibration] A calibration profile is necessary for each printer/paper/ink combination.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Color depth is only one aspect of color representation, expressing the precision with which the amount of each primary can be expressed; the other aspect is how broad a range of colors can be expressed (the gamut).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The definition of both color precision and gamut is accomplished with a color encoding specification which assigns a digital code value to a location in a color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The number of bits of resolved intensity in a color channel is also known as **radiometric resolution**, especially in the context of satellite images.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] With the relatively low color depth, the stored value is typically a number representing the index into a color map or palette (a form of vector quantization).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The colors available in the palette itself may be fixed by the hardware or modifiable by software.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Modifiable palettes are sometimes referred to as pseudocolor palettes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Old graphics chips, particularly those used in home computers and video game consoles, often have the ability to use a different palette per sprites and tiles in order to increase the maximum number of simultaneously displayed colors, while minimizing use of then-expensive memory (and bandwidth).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] For example, in the ZX Spectrum the picture is stored in a two-color format, but these two colors can be separately defined for each rectangular block of 8×8 pixels.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The palette itself has a color depth (number of bits per entry).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] While the best VGA systems only offered an 18-bit (262,144 color) palette from which colors could be chosen, all color Macintosh video hardware offered a 24-bit (16 million color) palette.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 24-bit palettes are nearly universal on any recent hardware or file format using them.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] If instead the color can be directly figured out from the pixel values, it is "direct color".
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Palettes were rarely used for depths greater than 12 bits per pixel, as the memory consumed by the palette would exceed the necessary memory for direct color on every pixel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 2 colors, often black and white direct color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Sometimes 1 meant black and 0 meant white, the inverse of modern standards.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Most of the first graphics displays were of this type, the X Window System was developed for such displays, and this was assumed for a 3M computer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] In the late 1980s there were professional displays with resolutions up to 300 dpi (the same as a contemporary laser printer) but color proved more popular.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 4 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Gray-scale early NeXTstation, color Macintoshes, Atari ST medium resolution.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 8 colors, almost always all combinations of full-intensity red, green, and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Many early home computers with TV displays, including the ZX Spectrum and BBC Micro.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 16 colors, usually from a selection of fixed palettes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Used by IBM CGA (at the lowest resolution), EGA, and by the least common denominator VGA standard at higher resolution.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Color Macintoshes, Atari ST low resolution, Commodore 64, and Amstrad CPCs also supported 4-bit color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 32 colors from a programmable palette, used by the Original Amiga chipset.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Used by the Master System, Enhanced Graphics Adapter, GIME for TRS-80 Color Computer 3, Pebble Time smartwatch (64 color e-paper display), and Parallax Propeller using the reference VGA circuit.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 256 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette: Most early color Unix workstations, Super VGA, color Macintosh, Atari TT, Amiga AGA chipset, Falcon030, Acorn Archimedes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Both X and Windows provided elaborate systems to try to allow each program to select its own palette, often resulting in incorrect colors in any window other than the one with focus.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some systems placed a color cube in the palette for a direct-color system (and so all programs would use the same palette).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Usually fewer levels of blue were provided than others, since the normal human eye is less sensitive to the blue component than to either red or green (two thirds of the eye's receptors process the longer wavelengths).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 4,096 colors, usually from a fully-programmable palette (though it was often set to a 16×16×16 color cube).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some Silicon Graphics systems, Color NeXTstation systems, and Amiga systems in HAM mode have this color depth.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] RGBA4444, a related 16 bpp representation providing the color cube and 16 levels of transparency, is a common texture format in mobile graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] In high-color systems, two bytes (16 bits) are stored for each pixel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Most often, each component (R, G, and B) is assigned 5 bits, plus one unused bit (or used for a mask channel or to switch to indexed color); this allows 32,768 colors to be represented.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However, an alternate assignment which reassigns the unused bit to the G channel allows 65,536 colors to be represented, but without transparency.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] These color depths are sometimes used in small devices with a color display, such as mobile phones, and are sometimes considered sufficient to display photographic images.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Among the first hardware to use the standard were the Sharp X68000 and IBM's Extended Graphics Array (XGA).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The term "high color" has recently been used to mean color depths greater than 24 bits.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] More expensive LCDs (typically IPS) can display 24-bit color depth or greater.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 24 bits almost always use 8 bits each of R, G, and B (8 bpc).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] As of 2018, 24-bit color depth is used by virtually every computer and phone display and the vast majority of image storage formats.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Almost all cases of 32 bits per pixel assigns 24 bits to the color, and the remaining 8 for the alpha channel (transparency) or left unused.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] While human eye can discriminate up to ten million colors, color gamuts employed by displays are typically smaller than the range of human vision.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] This means that 24 bits should be able to differentiate different colors with enough precision to prevent the perception of banding.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However, displays do not evenly distribute the colors in human perception space, so banding between some adjacent colors can still be perceived.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The DVD-Video and Blu-ray Disc standards support a bit depth of 8 bits per color in YCbCr with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] YCbCr can be losslessly converted to RGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] macOS and Classic Mac OS refer to 24-bit color as "millions" of colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The term *true color* is sometimes used to mean what this article calls *direct color*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] It is also often used to refer to all color depths greater than or equal to 24 bits.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some earlier systems placed three 10-bit channels in a 32-bit word, with 2 bits unused (or used as a 4-level alpha channel); the Cineon file format, for example, used this.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some SGI systems had 10-bit (or more) digital-to-analog converters for the video signal and could be set up to interpret data stored this way for display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] BMP files define this as one of its formats, and it is called "HiColor" by Microsoft.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Video cards with 10 bits per component started coming to market in the late 1990s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] An early example was the Radius ThunderPower card for the Macintosh, which included extensions for QuickDraw and Adobe Photoshop plugins to support editing 30-bit images.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some vendors call their 24-bit color depth with FRC panels 30-bit panels; however, true deep color displays have 10-bit or more color depth without FRC.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The HDMI 1.3 specification defines a bit depth of 30 bits (as well as 36 and 48 bit depths).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] As of 2026, 30 and 36 bit output is supported by all modern GPUs from Nvidia, AMD and Intel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] At WinHEC 2008, Microsoft announced that color depths of 30 bits and 48 bits would be supported in Windows 7, along with the wide color gamut scRGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] High Efficiency Video Coding (HEVC or H.265) defines the Main 10 profile, which allows for 8 or 10 bits per sample with 4:2:0 chroma subsampling.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The Main 10 profile was added at the October 2012 HEVC meeting based on proposal JCTVC-K0109 which proposed that a 10-bit profile be added to HEVC for consumer applications.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The proposal stated that this was to allow for improved video quality and to support the Rec.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] 2020 color space that will be used by UHDTV.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The second version of HEVC has five profiles that allow for a bit depth of 8 bits to 16 bits per sample.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Using 12 bits per color channel produces 36 bits, 68,719,476,736 colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 48 bits per pixel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] If an alpha channel of the same size is added then there are 64 bits per pixel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Some systems started using those bits for numbers outside the 0–1 range rather than for increasing the resolution.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Numbers greater than 1 were for colors brighter than the display could show, as in high-dynamic-range imaging (HDRI).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Negative numbers can increase the gamut to cover all possible colors, and for storing the results of filtering operations with negative filter coefficients.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The Pixar Image Computer used 12 bits to store numbers in the range [-1.5, 2.5), with 2 bits for the integer portion and 10 for the fraction.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The Cineon imaging system used 10-bit professional video displays with the video hardware adjusted so that a value of 95 was black and 685 was white.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The amplified signal tended to reduce the lifetime of the CRT.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] More bits also encouraged the storage of light as linear values, where the number directly corresponds to the amount of light emitted.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Linear levels makes calculation of computer graphics much easier.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However, linear color results in disproportionately more samples near white and fewer near black, so the quality of 16-bit linear is about equal to 12-bit sRGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Floating point numbers can represent linear light levels spacing the samples semi-logarithmically.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Floating point representations also allow for drastically larger dynamic ranges as well as negative values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Most systems first supported 32-bit per channel single-precision, which far exceeded the accuracy required for most applications.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] In 1999, Industrial Light & Magic released the open standard image file format OpenEXR which supported 16-bit-per-channel half-precision floating-point numbers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] At values near 1.0, half precision floating point values have only the precision of an 11-bit integer value, leading some graphics professionals to reject half-precision in situations where the extended dynamic range is not needed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Virtually all television displays and computer displays form images by varying the strength of just three primary colors: red, green, and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] For example, bright yellow is formed by roughly equal red and green contributions, with no blue contribution.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] For storing and manipulating images, alternative ways of expanding the traditional triangle exist: One can convert image coding to use fictitious primaries, that are not physically possible but that have the effect of extending the triangle to enclose a much larger color gamut.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] An equivalent, simpler change is to allow negative numbers in color channels, so that the represented colors can extend out of the color triangle formed by the primaries.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However these only extend the colors that can be represented in the image encoding; neither trick extends the gamut of colors that can actually be rendered on a display device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Supplementary colors can widen the color gamut of a display, since it is no longer limited to the interior of a triangle formed by three primaries at its corners, e.g. the CIE 1931 color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Recent technologies such as Texas Instruments's *BrilliantColor* augment the typical red, green, and blue channels with up to three other primaries: cyan, magenta, and yellow.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Cyan would be indicated by negative values in the red channel, magenta by negative values in the green channel, and yellow by negative values in the blue channel, validating the use of otherwise fictitious negative numbers in the color channels.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Mitsubishi and Samsung (among others) use *BrilliantColor* in some of their TV sets to extend the range of displayable colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The Sharp Aquos line of televisions has introduced Quattron technology, which augments the usual RGB pixel components with a yellow subpixel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However, formats and media that allow or make use of the extended color gamut are at present extremely rare.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] Because humans are overwhelmingly trichromats or dichromats one might suppose that adding a fourth "primary" color could provide no practical benefit.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] However humans can see a broader range of colors than a mixture of three colored lights can display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-depth] The deficit of colors is particularly noticeable in saturated shades of bluish green (shown as the left upper grey part of the horseshoe in the diagram) of RGB displays: Most humans can see more vivid blue-greens than any color video screen can display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color grading and color correction are often used synonymously as terms for this process and can include the generation of artistic color effects through creative blending and compositing of different layer masks of the source image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color grading is generally now performed in a digital process either in a controlled environment such as a color suite, and is usually done in a dim or dark environment.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The earlier photochemical film process, referred to as **color timing**, was performed at a film lab during printing by varying the intensity and color of light used to expose the rephotographed image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Since, with this process alone, the user was unable to immediately view the outcome of their changes, the use of a Hazeltine color analyzer was common for viewing these modifications in real time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In the 2000s, with the increase of digital technology, color grading in Hollywood films became more common.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color timing is used in reproducing film elements.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] "Color grading" was originally a lab term for the process of changing color appearance in film reproduction when going to the answer print or release print in the film reproduction chain.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] By the late 2010s, this film grading technique had become known as *color timing* and still involved changing the duration of exposure through different filters during the film development process.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color timing is specified in printer points which represent presets in a lab contact printer where 7 to 12 printer points represent one stop of light.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The number of points per stop varied based upon negative or print stock and different presets at film labs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In a film production, the creative team would meet with the “lab timer” who would watch a running film and make notes dependent upon the team's directions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] After the session, the timer would return to the lab and put the film negative on a device (the Hazeltine) which had preview filters with a controlled backlight, picking exact settings of each printer point for each scene.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] These settings were then punched onto a paper tape and fed to the high-speed printer where the negative was exposed through a backlight to a print stock.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Filter settings were changed on the fly to match the printer lights that were on the paper tape.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] For complex work such as visual effects shots, "wedges” running through combinations of filters were sometimes processed to aid the choice of the correct grading.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] This process is used wherever film materials are being reproduced.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] With the advent of television, broadcasters quickly realised the limitations of live television broadcasts and they turned to broadcasting feature films from release prints directly from a telecine.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] This was before 1956 when Ampex introduced the first Quadruplex videotape recorder (VTR) VRX-1000.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Live television shows could also be recorded to film and aired at different times in different time zones by filming a video monitor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The heart of this system was the *kinescope*, a device for recording a television broadcast to film.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The early telecine hardware was the "film chain" for broadcasting from film and utilized a film projector connected to a video camera.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In a cathode-ray tube (CRT) system, an electron beam is projected at a phosphor-coated envelope, producing a small spot of light.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] This beam is then scanned across a film frame from left to right, capturing the "vertical" frame information.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Horizontal scanning of the frame is then accomplished as the film moves past the CRT's beam.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Once this photon beam passes through the film frame, it encounters a series of dichroic mirrors which separate the image into its primary red, green and blue components.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] From there, each individual beam is reflected onto a photomultiplier tube (PMT) where the photons are converted into an electronic signal to be recorded to tape.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In a charge-coupled device (CCD) telecine, a white light is shone through the exposed film image onto a prism, which separates the image into the three primary colors, red, green and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Each beam of colored light is then projected at a different CCD, one for each color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The CCD converts the light into an electronic signal, and the telecine electronics modulate these into a video signal that can then be color graded.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Early color correction on Rank Cintel MkIII CRT telecine systems was accomplished by varying the primary gain voltages on each of the three photomultiplier tubes to vary the output of red, green and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Further advancements converted much of the color-processing equipment from analog to digital and then, with the next-generation telecine, the Ursa, the coloring process was completely digital in the 4:2:2 color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The Ursa Gold brought about color grading in the full 4:4:4 color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color correction control systems started with the Rank Cintel TOPSY (Telecine Operations Programming SYstem) in 1978.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In 1984 Da Vinci Systems introduced their first color corrector, a computer-controlled interface that would manipulate the color voltages on the Rank Cintel MkIII systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Since then, technology has improved to give extraordinary power to the digital colorist.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Today there are many companies making color correction control interfaces including Da Vinci Systems and Pandora International.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Some telecines are still in operation in 2018.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Note that some of these functions must be prioritized over others; for example, color grading may be done to ensure that the recorded colors match those of the original scene, whereas other times, the goal may instead be to establish a very artificial stylized look.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color grading is one of the most labour intensive parts of video editing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Traditionally, color grading was done towards practical goals.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] For example, in the film *Marianne*, grading was used so that night scenes could be filmed more cheaply in daylight.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Secondary color grading was originally used to establish color continuity; however, the trend today is increasingly moving towards creative goals such as improving the aesthetics of an image, establishing stylized looks, and setting the mood of a scene through color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Due to this trend, some colorists suggest the phrase "color enhancement" over "color correction".
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Primary color grading affects the whole image by providing control over the color density curves of red, green, blue color channels, across the entire frame.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Secondary grading can isolate a range of hue, saturation and brightness values to bring about alterations in hue, saturation and luminance only in that range, allowing the grading of secondary colors, while having a minimal or usually no effect on the remainder of the color spectrum.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Using digital grading, objects and color ranges within a scene can be isolated with precision and adjusted.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color tints can be manipulated and visual treatments pushed to extremes not physically possible with laboratory processing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] With these advancements, the color grading process has become increasingly similar to well-established digital painting techniques, ushering forth a new era of digital cinematography.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The evolution of digital color grading tools has advanced to the point where the colorist can use geometric shapes (such as mattes or masks in photo software such as Adobe Photoshop) to isolate color adjustments to specific areas of an image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] These tools can, for example, highlight a wall in the background and color only that wall, leaving the rest of the frame alone, or color everything but that wall.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Subsequent color grading tools (typically software-based) have the ability to use spline-based shapes for even greater control over isolating color adjustments.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Color keying is also used for isolating areas to adjust.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Inside and outside of area-based isolations, digital filtration can be applied to soften, sharpen or mimic the effects of traditional glass photographic filters.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] When trying to isolate a color adjustment on a moving subject, the colorist traditionally would manually move a mask to follow the subject.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In its most simple form, motion tracking software automates this time-consuming process using algorithms to evaluate the motion of a group of pixels.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] These techniques are generally derived from match moving techniques used in special effects and compositing work.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] From 2010, many films, such as *Hot Tub Time Machine* and *Iron Man 2,* began using the complementary colors orange and teal.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The evolution of the telecine device into film scanning allowed the digital information scanned from a film negative to be of sufficient resolution to transfer back to film.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In the early 1990s, Kodak developed the Cineon Film System to capture, manipulate, and record back to film and they called this the “Digital Intermediate”.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In the late 1990s, the films *Pleasantville* and *O Brother, Where Art Thou?* advanced the technology to the point that the creation of a digital intermediate was practical, which greatly expanded the capabilities of the digital telecine colorist to the traditionally-oriented world of feature films.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Since 2010, almost all feature films have gone through the DI process, while manipulation through photochemical processing is rare or used on archival films.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In Hollywood, *O Brother, Where Art Thou?* was the first film to be wholly digitally graded.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The negative was scanned with a Spirit DataCine at 2K resolution, then colors were digitally fine-tuned using a Pandora MegaDef color corrector on a Virtual DataCine.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The process took several weeks, and the resulting digital master was output to film again with a Kodak laser recorder to create a master internegative.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Modern motion picture processing typically uses both digital cameras and digital projectors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Calibrated devices are most commonly used to maintain a consistent appearance within the workflow.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] In early use, hardware-based systems (da Vinci 2K, Pandora International MegaDEF, etc.) have historically offered better performance but a smaller feature set than software-based systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Their real time performance was optimized to particular resolution and bit depths, as opposed to software platforms using standard computer industry hardware that often trade speed for resolution independence, e.g.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Apple's Color (previously Silicon Color Final Touch), ASSIMILATE SCRATCH, Adobe SpeedGrade and SGO Mistika.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] While hardware-based systems always offer real-time performance, some software-based systems need to pre-render as the complexity of the color grading increases.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] On the other hand, software-based systems tend to have more features such as spline-based windows/masks and advanced motion tracking.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The line between hardware and software no longer exists as many software-based color correctors (e.g.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Pablo, Mistika, SCRATCH, Autodesk Lustre, Nucoda Film Master and FilmLight's Baselight) use multi processor workstations and a GPU (graphics processing unit) as a means of hardware acceleration.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] As well, some newer software-based systems use a cluster of multiple parallel GPUs on the one computer system to improve performance at the very high resolutions required for feature film grading. e.g.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Some color grading software like Synthetic Aperture's Color Finesse runs solely as software and will even run on low-end computer systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] High-speed RAID arrays are an essential part of the process for all systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] Hardware systems are no longer common because of the price/performance of software systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-grading] The control panels are placed in a color suite for the colorist to operate the telecine remotely.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color management is necessary because different devices have different color capabilities and characteristics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] For example, a monitor may display colors differently than a printer can reproduce them.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Without color management, the same image may appear differently on different devices, leading to inconsistencies and inaccuracies.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] To achieve color management, a color profile is created for each device involved in the color workflow.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This profile describes the device's color capabilities and characteristics, such as its color gamut (range of colors it can display or reproduce) and color temperature.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] These profiles are then used to translate colors between devices, ensuring consistent and accurate color reproduction.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color management is particularly important in industries such as graphic design, photography, and printing, where accurate color representation is crucial.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] It helps to maintain color consistency throughout the entire workflow, from capturing an image to displaying or printing it.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Parts of color management are implemented in the operating system (OS), helper libraries, the application, and devices.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The type of color profile that is typically used is called an ICC profile.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] A cross-platform view of color management is the use of an ICC-compatible color management system.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] There are other approaches to color management besides using ICC profiles.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This is partly due to history and partly because of other needs than the ICC standard covers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The film and broadcasting industries make use of some of the same concepts, but they frequently rely on more limited boutique solutions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The film industry, for instance, often uses 3D LUTs (lookup table) to represent a complete color transformation for a specific RGB encoding.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] At the consumer level, system wide color management is available in most of Apple's products (macOS, iOS, iPadOS, watchOS).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Microsoft Windows lacks system wide color management and virtually all applications do not employ color management.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Windows' media player API is not color space aware, and if applications want to color manage videos manually, they have to incur significant performance and power consumption penalties.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Android supports system wide color management, but most devices ship with color management disabled.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Each color profile describes these colors relative to a standardized set of reference colors (the "Profile Connection Space").
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color-managed software then uses these standardized profiles to translate color from one device to another.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This is usually performed by a color management module (CMM).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] To describe the behavior of various output devices, they must be compared (measured) in relation to a standard color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Often a step called linearization is performed first, to undo the effect of gamma correction that was done to get the most out of limited 8-bit color paths.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Instruments used for measuring device colors include colorimeters and spectrophotometers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] As an intermediate result, the device gamut is described in the form of scattered measurement data.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The transformation of the scattered measurement data into a more regular form, usable by the application, is called *profiling*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Profiling is a complex process involving mathematics, intense computation, judgment, testing, and iteration.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] After the profiling is finished, an idealized color description of the device is created.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Calibration is like characterization, except that it can include the adjustment of the device, as opposed to just the measurement of the device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color management is sometimes sidestepped by calibrating devices to a common standard color space such as sRGB; when such calibration is done well enough, no color translations are needed to get all devices to handle colors consistently.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This avoidance of the complexity of color management was one of the goals in the development of sRGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Image formats themselves (such as TIFF, JPEG, PNG, EPS, PDF, and SVG) may contain embedded color profiles but are not required to do so by the image format.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The International Color Consortium standard was created to bring various developers and manufacturers together.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The ICC standard permits the exchange of output device characteristics and color spaces in the form of metadata.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This allows the embedding of color profiles into images as well as storing them in a database or a profile directory.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Working spaces, such as sRGB, Adobe RGB or ProPhoto are color spaces that facilitate good results while editing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] For instance, pixels with equal values of R,G,B should appear neutral.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Using a large (gamut) working space will lead to posterization, while using a small working space will lead to clipping.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This trade-off is a consideration for the critical image editor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color transformation, or color space conversion, is the transformation of the representation of a color from one color space to another.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This calculation is required whenever data is exchanged inside a color-managed chain and carried out by a Color Matching Module.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Transforming profiled color information to different output devices is achieved by referencing the profile data into a standard color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] It makes it easier to convert colors from one device to a selected standard color space and from that to the colors of another device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] By ensuring that the reference color space covers the many possible colors that humans can see, this concept allows one to exchange colors between many different color output devices.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Color transformations can be represented by two profiles (source profile and target profile) or by a devicelink profile.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In this process there are approximations involved which make sure that the image keeps its important color qualities and also gives an opportunity to control on how the colors are being changed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In the terminology of the International Color Consortium, a translation between two color spaces can go through a *profile connection space* (PCS): Color Space 1 → PCS (CIELAB or CIEXYZ) → Color space 2; conversions into and out of the PCS are each specified by a profile.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In nearly every translation process, we have to deal with the fact that the color gamut of different devices vary in range which makes an accurate reproduction impossible.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] They therefore need some rearrangement near the borders of the gamut.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Some colors must be shifted to the inside of the gamut, as they otherwise cannot be represented on the output device and would simply be clipped.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This so-called gamut mismatch occurs for example, when we translate from the RGB color space with a wider gamut into the CMYK color space with a narrower gamut range.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In this example, the dark highly saturated purplish-blue color of a typical computer monitor's "blue" primary is impossible to print on paper with a typical CMYK printer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The nearest approximation within the printer's gamut will be much less saturated.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Conversely, an inkjet printer's "cyan" primary, a saturated mid-brightness blue, is outside the gamut of a typical computer monitor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The color management system can utilize various methods to achieve desired results and give experienced users control of the gamut mapping behavior.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] When the gamut of source color space exceeds that of the destination, saturated colors are liable to become clipped (inaccurately represented), or more formally burned.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The color management module can deal with this problem in several ways.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The ICC specification includes four different rendering intents, listed below.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Before the actual rendering intent is carried out, one can temporarily simulate the rendering by soft proofing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Absolute colorimetry and relative colorimetry actually use the same table but differ in the adjustment for the white point media.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] If the output device has a much larger gamut than the source profile, i.e., all the colors in the source can be represented in the output, using the absolute colorimetry rendering intent would ideally (ignoring noise, precision, etc.) give an exact output of the specified CIELAB values.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Perceptually, the colors may appear incorrect, but instrument measurements of the resulting output would match the source.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Colors outside of the proof print system's possible color are mapped to the boundary of the color gamut.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Absolute colorimetry is useful to get an exact specified color (e.g., IBM blue), or to quantify the accuracy of mapping methods.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The goal in relative colorimetry is to be truthful to the specified color, with only a correction for the media.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Relative colorimetry is useful in proofing applications, since it can be used to get an idea of how a print on one device will appear on a different device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Media differences are the only thing that one really should adjust for, although some gamut mapping also needs to be applied.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Usually this is done in a way where hue and lightness are maintained at the cost of reduced saturation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] By default, in-gamut colors are unchanged, while out-of-gamut colors are clamped.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Relative colorimetric is the default rendering intent on many systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The perceptual intent smoothly moves out-of-gamut colors into gamut, preserving gradations, but distorts in-gamut colors in the process.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Like the saturation intent, the results really depend upon the profile maker.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This is even how some of the competitors in this market differentiate themselves.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The profile maker tries to make results pleasing on this intent.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Perceptual rendering is recommended for color separation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The saturation intent is designed to present eye-catching business graphics by preserving the saturation (colorfulness).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] It is most useful in charts and diagrams, where there is a discrete palette of colors that the designer wants saturated to make them intense, but where specific hue is less important.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In practice, photographers almost always use relative or perceptual intent, as for natural images, absolute causes color cast, while saturation produces unnatural colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] If an entire image is in-gamut, relative is perfect, but when there are out of gamut colors, which is preferable depends on a case-by-case basis.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] CMMs may offer options for BPC and partial chromatic adaptation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] A black point correction (BPC) is not applied for absolute colorimetric or devicelink profiles.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] For ICCv4, it is always applied to the perceptual intent.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] ICCv2 sRGB profiles differ among each other in a number of ways, one of which being whether BPC is applied.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Some well known CMMs are ColorSync, Adobe CMM, Little CMS, and ArgyllCMS.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] System wide color management is used in iOS, iPadOS and watchOS as well.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Microsoft Windows prior to Windows 10 recommends the sRGB color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Since Windows 10 with High Dynamic Range (HDR) enabled and since Windows 11 with Auto Color Management (ACM) enabled, it recommends the DCI-P3 color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Since 1997 color management in Windows is available through an ICC color management system: ICM (Image Color Management).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Beginning with Windows Vista, Microsoft introduced a new color architecture known as WCS (Windows Color System).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] WCS supplements the ICM system in Windows 2000 and Windows XP, originally written by Heidelberg.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Apps need to be aware of color management and tag the content appropriately to accurately display colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Otherwise, (unlike macOS) Windows will display the colors to the maximum extent of the display's gamut, resulting in over-saturated colors on wide-gamut displays.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] To fix this issue, Microsoft includes a new feature called "Auto Color Management" since Windows 11 2022.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] A few exception is the ICM profile includes the Video Card Gamma Table (VCGT) data, and the VCGT data will be applied globally.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Windows Photo Viewer from Windows 7 (also included in later Windows versions) performs proper color management, however, the newer Windows Photos app in Windows 8, 10, 11 does not perform legacy color management (ICM/WCS) until version v2022.31070.26005.0.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Other Windows components, including Microsoft Paint, Snipping Tool, Windows Desktop, Windows Explorer, do not perform legacy color management.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] In Windows 8, the DXVA API and the WIC API added support for color space conversion, but in Windows 8 it's still not support wide color gamut.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Unfortunately, the vast majority of personal applications do not use the Windows Color System.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] For applications that do employ color management (typically web browsers), color management tend to apply for only images and UI, but not videos.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This is because Windows' media player API is not color space aware.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Thus, browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge) are only able to do color management for images but not video.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] For the same reason, virtually no video players on Windows support color management (including the default Windows Movies & TV app and VLC Media Player), with Media Player Classic Home Cinema being a rare exception.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Windows 10 1607 supports High Dynamic Range (HDR).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Windows 11 22H2 supports Auto Color Management (ACM) which further optimized for OLED and/or wide-color gamut monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Applications can be updated to support ACM and wide-color gamut; Microsoft Edge, Google Chrome, Windows Photos and Windows Media Player 2022 are known to support ACM.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] While ACM can do color space conversion, but actual color management factors (such as color temperature and contrast) are also depend on OSD settings of monitor or TV set, and/or depend on software/driver settings of GPU/monitor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] On Android, system wide color management is introduced in Android Oreo 8.1.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] However, most Android phones are shipped with color management disabled (ex: 'adaptive' color profile on Google Pixel, 'vivid' color profile on Samsung Galaxy).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] This oversaturates sRGB content to the native display gamut, typically DCI-P3.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Users need to manually select the 'natural' color profile to enable color management, enabling accurate display of sRGB and P3 wide color content.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Operating systems that use the X Window System for graphics can use ICC profiles, and support for color management on Linux, still less mature than on other platforms, is coordinated through OpenICC at freedesktop.org and makes use of LittleCMS.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Certain image filetypes (TIFF and Photoshop) include the notion of color channels for specifying the *color mode* of the file.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The most commonly used channels are RGB (mainly for display (monitors) but also for some desktop printing) and CMYK (for commercial printing).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] An additional *alpha* channel may specify a transparency mask value.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Some image software (such as Photoshop) perform automatic color separation to maintain color information in CMYK mode using a specified ICC profile such as **US Web Coated (SWOP) v2**.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Adobe software includes its own color management engine - Adobe Color Engine.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] It is also available as a separate Color Management Module - Adobe CMM for use by non-Adobe applications that supports 3rd-party CMMs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] As of 2005, most web browsers ignored color profiles.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Notable exceptions were Safari, starting with version 2.0, and Firefox starting with version 3.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Although disabled by default in Firefox 3.0, ICC v2 and ICC v4 color management could be enabled by using an add-on or setting a configuration option.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] As of July 2019, Safari, Chrome and Firefox fully support color management.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Most browsers only do color management for images and CSS elements, but not video.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Regarding mobile browsers, Safari 13.1 (on iOS 13.4.1) recognizes the device color profile and can displays images accordingly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] Chrome 83 (on Android 9) ignores the display profile, simply converting all images to sRGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] As of 2023, Chrome 114, Android Browser 114 and Firefox for Android 115 support multiple colorspaces.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-management] The same is valid for their desktop counterparts: Chrome 118, Edge 114, Safari 16.6, Firefox 117 and Opera 100.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:3d-lookup-table/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics is responsible for displaying art and image data effectively and meaningfully to the consumer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It is also used for processing image data received from the physical world, such as photo and video content.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics development has had a significant impact on many types of media and has revolutionized animation, movies, advertising, and video games in general.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The term computer graphics has been used in a broad sense to describe "almost everything on computers that is not text or sound".
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Such imagery is found in and on television, newspapers, weather reports, and in a variety of medical investigations and surgical procedures.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A well-constructed graph can present complex statistics in a form that is easier to understand and interpret.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the media "such graphs are used to illustrate papers, reports, theses", and other presentation material.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Many tools have been developed to visualize data.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer-generated imagery can be categorized into several different types: two dimensional (2D), three dimensional (3D), and animated graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] As technology has improved, 3D computer graphics have become more common, but 2D computer graphics are still widely used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics has emerged as a sub-field of computer science which studies methods for digitally synthesizing and manipulating visual content.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The precursor sciences to the development of modern computer graphics were the advances in electrical engineering, electronics, and television that took place during the first half of the twentieth century.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Screens could display art since the Lumiere brothers' use of mattes to create special effects for the earliest films dating from 1895, but such displays were limited and not interactive.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The first cathode ray tube, the Braun tube, was invented in 1897 – it in turn would permit the oscilloscope and the military control panel – the more direct precursors of the field, as they provided the first two-dimensional electronic displays that responded to programmatic or user input.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] New kinds of displays were needed to process the wealth of information resulting from such projects, leading to the development of computer graphics as a discipline.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Early projects like the Whirlwind and SAGE Projects introduced the CRT as a viable display and interaction interface and introduced the light pen as an input device.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Ross of the Whirlwind SAGE system performed a personal experiment in which he wrote a small program that captured the movement of his finger and displayed its vector (his traced name) on a display scope.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] One of the first interactive video games to feature recognizable, interactive graphics – *Tennis for Two* – was created for an oscilloscope by William Higinbotham to entertain visitors in 1958 at Brookhaven National Laboratory and simulated a tennis match.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Ross, while working at MIT on transforming mathematic statements into computer generated 3D machine tool vectors, created a display scope image of a Disney cartoon character.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Electronics pioneer Hewlett-Packard went public in 1957 after incorporating the decade prior, and established strong ties with Stanford University through its founders, who were alumni.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This began the decades-long transformation of the southern San Francisco Bay Area into the world's leading computer technology hub – now known as Silicon Valley.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The field of computer graphics developed with the emergence of computer graphics hardware.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Further advances in computing led to greater advancements in interactive computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1959, the TX-2 computer was developed at MIT's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The TX-2 integrated a number of new man-machine interfaces.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A light pen could be used to draw sketches on the computer using Ivan Sutherland's revolutionary Sketchpad software.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Using a light pen, Sketchpad allowed one to draw simple shapes on the computer screen, save them and even recall them later.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The light pen itself had a small photoelectric cell in its tip.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This cell emitted an electronic pulse whenever it was placed in front of a computer screen and the screen's electron gun fired directly at it.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By simply timing the electronic pulse with the current location of the electron gun, it was easy to pinpoint exactly where the pen was on the screen at any given moment.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Once that was determined, the computer could then draw a cursor at that location.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Sutherland seemed to find the perfect solution for many of the graphics problems he faced.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Even today, many standards of computer graphics interfaces got their start with this early Sketchpad program.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] One example of this is in drawing constraints.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] If one wants to draw a square for example, they do not have to worry about drawing four lines perfectly to form the edges of the box.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] One can simply specify that they want to draw a box, and then specify the location and size of the box.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The software will then construct a perfect box, with the right dimensions and at the right location.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Another example is that Sutherland's software modeled objects – not just a picture of objects.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In other words, with a model of a car, one could change the size of the tires without affecting the rest of the car.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It could stretch the body of car without deforming the tires.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The phrase "computer graphics" has been credited to William Fetter, a graphic designer for Boeing in 1960.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Fetter in turn attributed it to Verne Hudson, also at Boeing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1961 another student at MIT, Steve Russell, created another important title in the history of video games, *Spacewar!* Written for the DEC PDP-1, *Spacewar* was an instant success and copies started flowing to other PDP-1 owners and eventually DEC got a copy.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The engineers at DEC used it as a diagnostic program on every new PDP-1 before shipping it.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The sales force picked up on this quickly enough and when installing new units, would run the "world's first video game" for their new customers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] At around the same time (1961–1962) in the University of Cambridge, Elizabeth Waldram wrote code to display radio-astronomy maps on a cathode ray tube.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Zajac, a scientist at Bell Telephone Laboratory (BTL), created a film called "Simulation of a two-giro gravity attitude control system" in 1963.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In this computer-generated film, Zajac showed how the attitude of a satellite could be altered as it orbits the Earth.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] He created the animation on an IBM 7090 mainframe computer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also at BTL, Ken Knowlton, Frank Sinden, Ruth A.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Weiss and Michael Noll started working in the computer graphics field.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Sinden created a film called *Force, Mass and Motion* illustrating Newton's laws of motion in operation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Around the same time, other scientists were creating computer graphics to illustrate their research.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] At Lawrence Radiation Laboratory, Nelson Max created the films *Flow of a Viscous Fluid* and *Propagation of Shock Waves in a Solid Form*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Boeing Aircraft created a film called *Vibration of an Aircraft*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also sometime in the early 1960s, automobiles would also provide a boost through the early work of Pierre Bézier at Renault, who used Paul de Casteljau's curves – now called Bézier curves after Bézier's work in the field – to develop 3d modeling techniques for Renault car bodies.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] These curves would form the foundation for much curve-modeling work in the field, as curves – unlike polygons – are mathematically complex entities to draw and model well.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It was not long before major corporations started taking an interest in computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] TRW, Lockheed-Georgia, General Electric and Sperry Rand are among the many companies that were getting started in computer graphics by the mid-1960s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] IBM was quick to respond to this interest by releasing the IBM 2250 graphics terminal, the first commercially available graphics computer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Ralph Baer, a supervising engineer at Sanders Associates, came up with a home video game in 1966 that was later licensed to Magnavox and called the Odyssey.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] While very simplistic, and requiring fairly inexpensive electronic parts, it allowed the player to move points of light around on a screen.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It was the first consumer computer graphics product.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Evans was director of engineering at Bendix Corporation's computer division from 1953 to 1962, after which he worked for the next five years as a visiting professor at Berkeley.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] There he continued his interest in computers and how they interfaced with people.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1966, the University of Utah recruited Evans to form a computer science program, and computer graphics quickly became his primary interest.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This new department would become the world's primary research center for computer graphics through the 1970s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also, in 1966, Ivan Sutherland continued to innovate at MIT when he invented the first computer-controlled head-mounted display (HMD).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It displayed two separate wireframe images, one for each eye.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This allowed the viewer to see the computer scene in stereoscopic 3D.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The heavy hardware required for supporting the display and tracker was called the Sword of Damocles because of the potential danger if it were to fall upon the wearer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] After receiving his Ph.D. from MIT, Sutherland became Director of Information Processing at ARPA (Advanced Research Projects Agency), and later became a professor at Harvard.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] There Sutherland perfected his HMD; twenty years later, NASA would re-discover his techniques in their virtual reality research.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] At Utah, Sutherland and Evans were highly sought after consultants by large companies, but they were frustrated at the lack of graphics hardware available at the time, so they started formulating a plan to start their own company.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1968, Dave Evans and Ivan Sutherland founded the first computer graphics hardware company, Evans & Sutherland.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] While Sutherland originally wanted the company to be located in Cambridge, Massachusetts, Salt Lake City was instead chosen due to its proximity to the professors' research group at the University of Utah.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1969, the ACM initiated A Special Interest Group on Graphics (SIGGRAPH) which organizes conferences, graphics standards, and publications within the field of computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By 1973, the first annual SIGGRAPH conference was held, which has become one of the focuses of the organization.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] SIGGRAPH has grown in size and importance as the field of computer graphics has expanded over time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Subsequently, a number of breakthroughs in the field occurred at the University of Utah in the 1970s, which had hired Ivan Sutherland.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Evans to teach an advanced computer graphics class, which contributed a great deal of founding research to the field and taught several students who would grow to found several of the industry's most important companies – namely Pixar, Silicon Graphics, and Adobe Systems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Tom Stockham led the image processing group at UU which worked closely with the computer graphics lab.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] One of these students was Edwin Catmull.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Catmull had just come from The Boeing Company and had been working on his degree in physics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Growing up on Disney, Catmull loved animation yet quickly discovered that he did not have the talent for drawing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Now Catmull (along with many others) saw computers as the natural progression of animation and they wanted to be part of the revolution.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The first computer animation that Catmull saw was his own.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] He created an animation of his hand opening and closing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] He also pioneered texture mapping to paint textures on three-dimensional models in 1974, now considered one of the fundamental techniques in 3D modeling.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It became one of his goals to produce a feature-length motion picture using computer graphics – a goal he would achieve two decades later after his founding role in Pixar.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the same class, Fred Parke created an animation of his wife's face.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The two animations were included in the 1976 feature film Futureworld.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] As the UU computer graphics laboratory was attracting people from all over, John Warnock was another of those early pioneers; he later founded Adobe Systems and created a revolution in the publishing world with his PostScript page description language.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Adobe would go on later to create the industry standard photo editing software in Adobe Photoshop and a prominent movie industry special effects program in Adobe After Effects.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] James Clark was also there; he later founded Silicon Graphics, a maker of advanced rendering systems that would dominate the field of high-end graphics until the early 1990s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A major advance in 3D computer graphics was created at UU by these early pioneers – hidden surface determination.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In order to draw a representation of a 3D object on the screen, the computer must determine which surfaces are "behind" the object from the viewer's perspective, and thus should be "hidden" when the computer creates (or renders) the image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The 3D Core Graphics System (or **Core**) was the first graphical standard to be developed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A group of 25 experts of the ACM Special Interest Group SIGGRAPH developed this "conceptual framework".
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The specifications were published in 1977, and it became a foundation for many future developments in the field.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also in the 1970s, Henri Gouraud, Jim Blinn and Bui Tuong Phong contributed to the foundations of shading in CGI via the development of the Gouraud shading and Blinn–Phong shading models, allowing graphics to move beyond a "flat" look to a look more accurately portraying depth.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Jim Blinn also innovated further in 1978 by introducing bump mapping, a technique for simulating uneven surfaces, and the predecessor to many more advanced kinds of mapping used today.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The modern videogame arcade as is known today was birthed in the 1970s, with the first arcade games using real-time 2D sprite graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] *Pong* in 1972 was one of the first hit arcade cabinet games.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] *Speed Race* in 1974 featured sprites moving along a vertically scrolling road.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] *Gun Fight* in 1975 featured human-looking animated characters, while *Space Invaders* in 1978 featured a large number of animated figures on screen; both used a specialized barrel shifter circuit made from discrete chips to help their Intel 8080 microprocessor animate their framebuffer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The 1980s began to see the commercialization of computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] As the home computer proliferated, a subject which had previously been an academics-only discipline was adopted by a much larger audience, and the number of computer graphics developers increased significantly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] NEC's μPD7220 was the first GPU, fabricated on a fully integrated NMOS VLSI chip.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It supported up to 1024x1024 resolution, and laid the foundations for the emerging PC graphics market.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It was used in a number of graphics cards, and was licensed for clones such as the Intel 82720, the first of Intel's graphics processing units.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] MOS memory also became cheaper in the early 1980s, enabling the development of affordable framebuffer memory, notably video RAM (VRAM) introduced by Texas Instruments (TI) in the mid-1980s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1984, Hitachi released the ARTC HD63484, the first complementary MOS (CMOS) GPU.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It was capable of displaying high-resolution in color mode and up to 4K resolution in monochrome mode, and it was used in a number of graphics cards and terminals during the late 1980s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1986, TI introduced the TMS34010, the first fully programmable MOS graphics processor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics terminals during this decade became increasingly intelligent, semi-standalone and standalone workstations.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics and application processing were increasingly migrated to the intelligence in the workstation, rather than continuing to rely on central mainframe and minicomputers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The Orca 3000 was based on the 16-bit Motorola 68000 microprocessor and AMD bit-slice processors, and had Unix as its operating system.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It was targeted squarely at the sophisticated end of the design engineering sector.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Artists and graphic designers began to see the personal computer, particularly the Amiga and Macintosh, as a serious design tool, one that could save time and draw more accurately than other methods.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The Macintosh remains a highly popular tool for computer graphics among graphic design studios and businesses.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Modern computers, dating from the 1980s, often use graphical user interfaces (GUI) to present data and information with symbols, icons and pictures, rather than text.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics are one of the five key elements of multimedia technology.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the field of realistic rendering, Japan's Osaka University developed the LINKS-1 Computer Graphics System, a supercomputer that used up to 257 Zilog Z8001 microprocessors, in 1982, for the purpose of rendering realistic 3D computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] According to the Information Processing Society of Japan: "The core of 3D image rendering is calculating the luminance of each pixel making up a rendered surface from the given viewpoint, light source, and object position.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The LINKS-1 system was developed to realize an image rendering methodology in which each pixel could be parallel processed independently using ray tracing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By developing a new software methodology specifically for high-speed image rendering, LINKS-1 was able to rapidly render highly realistic images." The LINKS-1 was the world's most powerful computer, as of 1984.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also in the field of realistic rendering, the general rendering equation of David Immel and James Kajiya was developed in 1986 – an important step towards implementing global illumination, which is necessary to pursue photorealism in computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The continuing popularity of *Star Wars* and other science fiction franchises were relevant in cinematic CGI at this time, as Lucasfilm and Industrial Light & Magic became known as the "go-to" house by many other studios for topnotch computer graphics in film.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Important advances in chroma keying ("bluescreening", etc.) were made for the later films of the original trilogy.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the late 1980s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) computers were used to create some of the first fully computer-generated short films at Pixar, and Silicon Graphics machines were considered a high-water mark for the field during the decade.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] For the arcades, advances were made in commercial, real-time 3D graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1988, the first dedicated real-time 3D graphics boards were introduced for arcades, with the Namco System 21 and Taito Air System.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] On the professional side, Evans & Sutherland and SGI developed 3D raster graphics hardware that directly influenced the later single-chip graphics processing unit (GPU), a technology where a separate and very powerful chip is used in parallel processing with a CPU to optimize graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The decade also saw computer graphics applied to many additional professional markets, including location-based entertainment and education with the E&S Digistar, vehicle design, vehicle simulation, and chemistry.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The 1990s' highlight was the emergence of 3D modeling on a mass scale and an rise in the quality of CGI generally.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By the end of the decade, the GPU would begin its rise to the prominence it still enjoys today.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The field began to see the first rendered graphics that could truly pass as photorealistic to the untrained eye (though they could not yet do so with a trained CGI artist) and 3D graphics became far more popular in gaming, multimedia, and animation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In film, Pixar began its serious commercial rise in this era under Edwin Catmull, with its first major film release, in 1995 – *Toy Story* – a critical and commercial success of nine-figure magnitude.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The studio to invent the programmable shader would go on to have many animated hits, and its work on prerendered video animation is still considered an industry leader and research trail breaker.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In video games, in 1992, *Virtua Racing*, running on the Sega Model 1 arcade system board, laid the foundations for fully 3D racing games and popularized real-time 3D polygonal graphics among a wider audience in the video game industry.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The Sega Model 2 in 1993 and Sega Model 3 in 1996 subsequently pushed the boundaries of commercial, real-time 3D graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Back on the PC, *Wolfenstein 3D*, *Doom* and *Quake*, three of the first massively popular 3D first-person shooter games, were released by id Software to critical and popular acclaim during this decade using a rendering engine innovated primarily by John Carmack.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The Sony PlayStation, Sega Saturn, and Nintendo 64, among other consoles, sold in the millions and popularized 3D graphics for home gamers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Certain late-1990s first-generation 3D titles became seen as influential in popularizing 3D graphics among console users, such as platform games *Super Mario 64* and *The Legend of Zelda: Ocarina of Time*, and early 3D fighting games like *Virtua Fighter*, *Battle Arena Toshinden*, and *Tekken*.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Technology and algorithms for rendering continued to improve greatly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In 1996, Krishnamurty and Levoy invented normal mapping – an improvement on Jim Blinn's bump mapping.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 1999 saw Nvidia release the seminal GeForce 256, the first home video card billed as a graphics processing unit or GPU, which in its own words contained "integrated transform, lighting, triangle setup/clipping, and rendering engines".
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By the end of the decade, computers adopted common frameworks for graphics processing such as DirectX and OpenGL.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Since then, computer graphics have only become more detailed and realistic, due to more powerful graphics hardware and 3D modeling software.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] AMD also became a leading developer of graphics boards in this decade, creating a "duopoly" in the field which exists this day.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] CGI became ubiquitous in earnest during this era.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Video games and CGI cinema had spread the reach of computer graphics to the mainstream by the late 1990s and continued to do so at an accelerated pace in the 2000s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] CGI was also adopted *en masse* for television advertisements widely in the late 1990s and 2000s, and so became familiar to a massive audience.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The continued rise and increasing sophistication of the graphics processing unit were crucial to this decade, and 3D rendering capabilities became a standard feature as 3D-graphics GPUs became considered a necessity for desktop computer makers to offer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The Nvidia GeForce line of graphics cards dominated the market in the early decade with occasional significant competing presence from ATI.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] As the decade progressed, even low-end machines usually contained a 3D-capable GPU of some kind as Nvidia and AMD both introduced low-priced chipsets and continued to dominate the market.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer graphics used in films and video games gradually began to be realistic to the point of entering the uncanny valley.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] CGI movies proliferated, with traditional animated cartoon films like Ice Age and Madagascar as well as numerous Pixar offerings like Finding Nemo dominating the box office in this field.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The *Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within*, released in 2001, was the first fully computer-generated feature film to use photorealistic CGI characters and be fully made with motion capture.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The film was not a box-office success, however.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Some commentators have suggested this may be partly because the lead CGI characters had facial features which fell into the "uncanny valley".
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Other animated films like *The Polar Express* drew attention at this time as well.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] *Star Wars* also resurfaced with its prequel trilogy and the effects continued to set a bar for CGI in film.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In videogames, the Sony PlayStation 2 and 3, the Microsoft Xbox line of consoles, and offerings from Nintendo such as the GameCube maintained a large following, as did the Windows PC.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Microsoft made a decision to expose DirectX more easily to the independent developer world with the XNA program, but it was not a success.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] DirectX itself remained a commercial success, however.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] OpenGL continued to mature as well, and it and DirectX improved greatly; the second-generation shader languages HLSL and GLSL began to be popular in this decade.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In scientific computing, the GPGPU technique to pass large amounts of data bidirectionally between a GPU and CPU was invented; speeding up analysis on many kinds of bioinformatics and molecular biology experiments.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The technique has also been used for Bitcoin mining and has applications in computer vision.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the 2010s, CGI has been nearly ubiquitous in video, pre-rendered graphics are nearly scientifically photorealistic, and real-time graphics on a suitably high-end system may simulate photorealism to the untrained eye.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Shaders are now very nearly a necessity for advanced work in the field, providing considerable complexity in manipulating pixels, vertices, and textures on a per-element basis, and countless possible effects.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Their shader languages HLSL and GLSL are active fields of research and development.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Experiments into the processing power required to provide graphics in real time at ultra-high-resolution modes like 4K Ultra HD begun, though beyond reach of all but the highest-end hardware.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In cinema, most animated movies are CGI now; many animated CGI films are made per year, but few, if any, attempt photorealism due to continuing fears of the uncanny valley.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In videogames, the Microsoft Xbox One, Sony PlayStation 4, and Nintendo Switch dominated the home space and were all capable of advanced 3D graphics; Windows was still one of the most active gaming platforms as well.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In the 2020s', advances in ray-tracing technology allowed it to be used for real-time rendering, as well as AI-powered graphics for generating or upscaling frames.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] While ray-tracing existed before, Nvidia was the first to push for ray-tracing with ray-tracing cores, as well as for AI with DLSS and Tensor cores.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] AMD followed suit with the same; FSR, Tensor cores and ray-tracing cores.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 2D computer graphics are the computer-based generation of digital images—mostly from models, such as digital image, and by techniques specific to them.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 2D computer graphics are mainly used in applications that were originally developed upon traditional printing and drawing technologies such as typography.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A large form of digital art, pixel art is created through the use of raster graphics software, where images are edited on the pixel level.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics in most old (or relatively limited) computer and video games, graphing calculator games, and many mobile phone games are mostly pixel art.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A sprite is a two-dimensional image or animation that is integrated into a larger scene.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Initially including just graphical objects handled separately from the memory bitmap of a video display, this now includes various manners of graphical overlays.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Originally, sprites were a method of integrating unrelated bitmaps so that they appeared to be part of the normal bitmap on a screen, such as creating an animated character that can be moved on a screen without altering the data defining the overall screen.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Such sprites can be created by either electronic circuitry or software.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In circuitry, a hardware sprite is a hardware construct that employs custom DMA channels to integrate visual elements with the main screen in that it super-imposes two discrete video sources.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Software can simulate this through specialized rendering methods.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Vector graphics formats are complementary to raster graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Raster graphics is the representation of images as an array of pixels and is typically used for the representation of photographic images.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Vector graphics consists of encoding information about shapes and colors that comprise the image, which can allow for more flexibility in rendering.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] There are instances when working with vector tools and formats is best practice, and instances when working with raster tools and formats is best practice.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] There are times when both formats come together.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] An understanding of the advantages and limitations of each technology and the relationship between them is most likely to result in efficient and effective use of tools.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Since the mid-2010s, as a result of advances in deep neural networks, models have been created which take as input a natural language description and produces as output an image matching that description.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Text-to-image models generally combine a language model, which transforms the input text into a latent representation, and a generative image model, which produces an image conditioned on that representation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The most effective models have generally been trained on massive amounts of image and text data scraped from the web.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] By 2022, the best of these models, for example Dall-E 2 and Stable Diffusion, are able to create images in a range of styles, ranging from imitations of living artists to near-photorealistic, in a matter of seconds, given powerful enough hardware.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 3D graphics, compared to 2D graphics, are graphics that use a three-dimensional representation of geometric data.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] For the purpose of performance, this is stored in the computer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This includes images that may be for later display or for real-time viewing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Despite these differences, 3D computer graphics rely on similar algorithms as 2D computer graphics do in the frame and raster graphics (like in 2D) in the final rendered display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In computer graphics software, the distinction between 2D and 3D is occasionally blurred; 2D applications may use 3D techniques to achieve effects such as lighting, and primarily 3D may use 2D rendering techniques.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 3D computer graphics are the same as 3D models.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The model is contained within the graphical data file, apart from the rendering.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] However, there are differences that include the 3D model being the representation of any 3D object.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Until visually displayed, a model is not graphic.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Due to printing, 3D models are not only confined to virtual space.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 3D rendering is how a model can be displayed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Also can be used in non-graphical computer simulations and calculations.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Computer animation is the art of creating moving images via the use of computers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It is a subfield of computer graphics and animation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Increasingly it is created by means of 3D computer graphics, though 2D computer graphics are still widely used for stylistic, low bandwidth, and faster real-time rendering needs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Sometimes the target of the animation is the computer itself, but sometimes the target is another medium, such as film.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It is also referred to as CGI (Computer-generated imagery or computer-generated imaging), especially when used in films.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Virtual entities may contain and be controlled by assorted attributes, such as transform values (location, orientation, and scale) stored in an object's transformation matrix.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Animation is the change of an attribute over time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Multiple methods of achieving animation exist; the rudimentary form is based on the creation and editing of keyframes, each storing a value at a given time, per attribute to be animated.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The 2D/3D graphics software will change with each keyframe, creating an editable curve of a value mapped over time, in which results in animation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] To create the illusion of movement, an image is displayed on the computer screen then quickly replaced by a new image that is similar to the previous image, but shifted slightly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This technique is identical to the illusion of movement in television and motion pictures.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Images are typically created by devices such as cameras, mirrors, lenses, telescopes, microscopes, etc.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Digital images include both vector images and raster images, but raster images are more commonly used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] In digital imaging, a pixel (or picture element) is a single point in a raster image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Pixels are placed on a regular 2-dimensional grid, and are often represented using dots or squares.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Each pixel is a sample of an original image, where more samples typically provide a more accurate representation of the original.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The intensity of each pixel is variable; in color systems, each pixel typically has three subpixels such as red, green, and blue.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics are visual representations on a surface, such as a computer screen.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Examples are photographs, drawing, graphics designs, maps, engineering drawings, or other images.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphics often combine text and illustration.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Graphic design may consist of the deliberate selection, creation, or arrangement of typography alone, as in a brochure, flier, poster, web site, or book without any other element.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Clarity or effective communication may be the objective, association with other cultural elements may be sought, or merely, the creation of a distinctive style.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Primitives are basic units which a graphics system may combine to create more complex images or models.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Examples would be sprites and character maps in 2D video games, geometric primitives in CAD, or polygons or triangles in 3D rendering.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Primitives may be supported in hardware for efficient rendering, or the building blocks provided by a graphics application.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Rendering is the generation of a 2D image from a 3D model by means of computer programs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A scene file contains objects in a strictly defined language or data structure; it would contain geometry, viewpoint, texturing, lighting, and shading information as a description of the virtual scene.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The data contained in the scene file is then passed to a rendering program to be processed and output to a digital image or raster graphics image file.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The rendering program is usually built into the computer graphics software, though others are available as plug-ins or entirely separate programs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The term "rendering" may be by analogy with an "artist's rendering" of a scene.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Although the technical details of rendering methods vary, the general challenges to overcome in producing a 2D image from a 3D representation stored in a scene file are outlined as the graphics pipeline along a rendering device, such as a GPU.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A GPU is a device able to assist the CPU in calculations.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] If a scene is to look relatively realistic and predictable under virtual lighting, the rendering software should solve the rendering equation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The rendering equation does not account for all lighting phenomena, but is a general lighting model for computer-generated imagery.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 'Rendering' is also used to describe the process of calculating effects in a video editing file to produce final video output.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] is a method of mapping three dimensional points to a two dimensional plane.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] As most current methods for displaying graphical data are based on planar two dimensional media, the use of this type of projection is widespread.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] It is a process used in drawing for depicting levels of darkness on paper by applying media more densely or with a darker shade for darker areas, and less densely or with a lighter shade for lighter areas.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] where perpendicular lines of varying closeness are drawn in a grid pattern to shade an area.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The closer the lines are together, the darker the area appears.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Likewise, the farther apart the lines are, the lighter the area appears.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A texture map is applied (mapped) to the surface of a shape, or polygon.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This process is akin to applying patterned paper to a plain white box.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Multitexturing is the use of more than one texture at a time on a polygon.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] to simulate mirror-like reflectivity, also called gloss.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Anti-aliasing methods rectify such problems, resulting in imagery more pleasing to the viewer, but can be somewhat computationally expensive.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] ) are able to be employed, then customized for the most efficient rendering performance versus quality of the resultant imagery; a graphics artist should consider this trade-off if anti-aliasing methods are to be used.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] help to solve texture-related aliasing problems.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Volume rendering is a technique used to display a 2D projection of a 3D discretely sampled data set.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A typical 3D data set is a group of 2D slice images acquired by a CT or MRI scanner.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Usually these are acquired in a regular pattern (e.g., one slice every millimeter) and usually have a regular number of image pixels in a regular pattern.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] This is an example of a regular volumetric grid, with each volume element, or voxel represented by a single value that is obtained by sampling the immediate area surrounding the voxel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 3D modeling is the process of developing a mathematical, wireframe representation of any three-dimensional object, called a "3D model", via specialized software.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] Models may be created automatically or manually; the manual modeling process of preparing geometric data for 3D computer graphics is similar to plastic arts such as sculpting.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] 3D models may be created using multiple approaches: use of NURBs to generate accurate and smooth surface patches, polygonal mesh modeling (manipulation of faceted geometry), or polygonal mesh subdivision (advanced tessellation of polygons, resulting in smooth surfaces similar to NURB models).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] A 3D model can be displayed as a two-dimensional image through a process called *3D rendering*, used in a computer simulation of physical phenomena, or animated directly for other purposes.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p01] The model can also be physically created using 3D Printing devices.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] was a pioneer in computer animation and digital fine art and created the first computer art in 1964.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] is a leading innovator in computer graphics.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] Greenberg was the founding director of the NSF Center for Computer Graphics and Scientific Visualization.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] He began creating digital art in 1962, making him one of the earliest digital artists.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] is a former professor of computer science.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] The study of computer graphics is a sub-field of computer science which studies methods for digitally synthesizing and manipulating visual content.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] Although the term often refers to three-dimensional computer graphics, it also encompasses two-dimensional graphics and image processing.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] As an academic discipline, computer graphics studies the manipulation of visual and geometric information using computational techniques.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] It focuses on the *mathematical* and *computational* foundations of image generation and processing rather than purely aesthetic issues.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-graphics-p02] Computer graphics is often differentiated from the field of visualization, although the two fields have many similarities.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A **computer monitor** is an output device that displays information in pictorial or textual form.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A discrete monitor comprises a visual display, support electronics, power supply, housing, electrical connectors, and external user controls.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The display in modern monitors is typically an LCD with LED backlight, having by the 2010s replaced CCFL backlit LCDs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Before the mid-2000s, most monitors used a cathode ray tube (CRT) as the image output technology.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A monitor is typically connected to its host computer via DisplayPort, HDMI, USB-C, DVI, or VGA.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Monitors sometimes use other proprietary connectors and signals to connect to a computer, which is less common.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Originally computer monitors were used for data processing while television sets were used for video.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] From the 1980s onward, computers (and their monitors) have been used for both data processing and video, while television sets have implemented some computer functionality.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Modern computer monitors are often functionally interchangeable with television sets and vice versa.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] As most computer monitors do not include integrated speakers, TV tuners, or remote controls, external components such as a DTA box may be needed to use a computer monitor as a TV set.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Early electronic computer front panels were fitted with an array of light bulbs where the state of each particular bulb would indicate the on/off state of a particular register bit inside the computer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This allowed the engineers operating the computer to monitor the internal state of the machine, so this panel of lights came to be known as the 'monitor'.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] As early monitors were only capable of displaying a very limited amount of information and were very transient, they were rarely considered for program output.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Instead, a line printer was the primary output device, while the monitor was limited to keeping track of the program's operation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Computer monitors were formerly known as **visual display units** (**VDU**), particularly in British English.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This term mostly fell out of use by the 1990s.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Multiple technologies have been used for computer monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Until the 21st century most used cathode ray tubes but they have largely been superseded by LCD monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The first computer monitors used cathode ray tubes (CRTs).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The display was monochromatic and far less sharp and detailed than on a modern monitor, necessitating the use of relatively large text and severely limiting the amount of information that could be displayed at one time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] High-resolution CRT displays were developed for specialized military, industrial and scientific applications but they were far too costly for general use; wider commercial use became possible after the release of a slow, but affordable Tektronix 4010 terminal in 1972.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Either computer could be connected to the antenna terminals of an ordinary color TV set or used with a purpose-made CRT color monitor for optimum resolution and color quality.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Lagging several years behind, in 1981 IBM introduced the Color Graphics Adapter, which could display four colors with a resolution of 320 × 200 pixels, or it could produce 640 × 200 pixels with two colors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In 1984 IBM introduced the Enhanced Graphics Adapter which was capable of producing 16 colors and had a resolution of 640 × 350.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] During the following decade, maximum display resolutions gradually increased and prices continued to fall as CRT technology remained dominant in the PC monitor market into the new millennium, partly because it remained cheaper to produce.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] CRTs still offer color, grayscale, motion, and latency advantages over today's LCDs, but improvements to the latter have made them much less obvious.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The dynamic range of early LCD panels was very poor, and although text and other motionless graphics were sharper than on a CRT, an LCD characteristic known as pixel lag caused moving graphics to appear noticeably smeared and blurry.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] There are multiple technologies that have been used to implement liquid-crystal displays (LCD).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Throughout the 1990s, the primary use of LCD technology as computer monitors was in laptops where the lower power consumption, lighter weight, and smaller physical size of LCDs justified the higher price versus a CRT.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Commonly, the same laptop would be offered with an assortment of display options at increasing price points: (active or passive) monochrome, passive color, or active matrix color (TFT).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] As volume and manufacturing capability have improved, the monochrome and passive color technologies were dropped from most product lines.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] TFT-LCD is a variant of LCD which is now the dominant technology used for computer monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The first standalone LCDs appeared in the mid-1990s selling for high prices.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] As prices declined they became more popular, and by 1997 were competing with CRT monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Among the first desktop LCD computer monitors were the Eizo FlexScan L66 in the mid-1990s, the SGI 1600SW, Apple Studio Display and the ViewSonic VP140 in 1998.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In 2003, LCDs outsold CRTs for the first time, becoming the primary technology used for computer monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The physical advantages of LCD over CRT monitors are that LCDs are lighter, smaller, and consume less power.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In terms of performance, LCDs produce less or no flicker, reducing eyestrain, sharper image at native resolution, and better checkerboard contrast.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Many specialized fields such as vision science remain dependent on CRTs, the best LCD monitors having achieved moderate temporal accuracy, and so can be used only if their poor spatial accuracy is unimportant.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] High dynamic range (HDR) has been implemented into high-end LCD monitors to improve grayscale accuracy.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Since around the late 2000s, widescreen LCD monitors have become popular, in part due to television series, motion pictures and video games transitioning to widescreen, which makes squarer monitors unsuited to display them correctly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Organic light-emitting diode (OLED) monitors provide most of the benefits of both LCD and CRT monitors with few of their drawbacks, though much like plasma panels or CRTs they suffer from burn-in, and are comparatively more expensive.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] On two-dimensional display devices such as computer monitors the display size or viewable image size is the actual amount of screen space that is available to display a picture, video or working space, without obstruction from the bezel or other aspects of the unit's design.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The main measurements for display devices are width, height, total area and the diagonal.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The size of a display is usually given by manufacturers diagonally, i.e. as the distance between two opposite screen corners.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This method of measurement is inherited from the method used for the first generation of CRT television when picture tubes with circular faces were in common use.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Being circular, it was the external diameter of the glass envelope that described their size.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Since these circular tubes were used to display rectangular images, the diagonal measurement of the rectangular image was smaller than the diameter of the tube's face (due to the thickness of the glass).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This method continued even when cathode ray tubes were manufactured as rounded rectangles; it had the advantage of being a single number specifying the size and was not confusing when the aspect ratio was universally 4:3.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] With the introduction of flat-panel technology, the diagonal measurement became the actual diagonal of the visible display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This meant that an eighteen-inch LCD had a larger viewable area than an eighteen-inch cathode ray tube.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Estimation of monitor size by the distance between opposite corners does not take into account the display aspect ratio, so that for example a 16:9 21-inch (53 cm) widescreen display has less area, than a 21-inch (53 cm) 4:3 screen.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Until about 2001, most computer monitors had a 4:3 aspect ratio and some had 5:4 or 8:7.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Between 2001 and 2006, monitors with 16:9 and mostly 16:10 (8:5) aspect ratios became commonly available, first in laptops and later also in standalone monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Reasons for this transition included productive uses (i.e. field of view in video games and movie viewing) such as the word processor display of two standard letter pages side by side, as well as CAD displays of large-size drawings and application menus at the same time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In 2008 16:10 became the most common sold aspect ratio for LCD monitors and the same year 16:10 was the mainstream standard for laptops and notebook computers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In 2010, the computer industry started to move over from 16:10 to 16:9 because 16:9 was chosen to be the standard high-definition television display size, and because they were cheaper to manufacture.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] In 2011, non-widescreen displays with 4:3 aspect ratios were only being manufactured in small quantities.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The resolution for computer monitors has increased over time.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Since 2009, the most commonly sold resolution for computer monitors is 1920 × 1080, shared with the 1080p of HDTV.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Before 2013 mass market LCD monitors were limited to 2560 × 1600 at 30 in (76 cm), excluding niche professional monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] By 2015 most major display manufacturers had released 3840 × 2160 (4K UHD) displays, and the first 7680 × 4320 (8K) monitors had begun shipping.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Every RGB monitor has its own color gamut, bounded in chromaticity by a color triangle.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Some of these triangles are smaller than the sRGB triangle, some are larger.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Colors are typically encoded by 8 bits per primary color.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The RGB value [255, 0, 0] represents red, but slightly different colors in different color spaces such as Adobe RGB and sRGB.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Displaying sRGB-encoded data on wide-gamut devices can give an unrealistic result.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The gamut is a property of the monitor; the image color space can be forwarded as Exif metadata in the picture.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] As long as the monitor gamut is wider than the color space gamut, correct display is possible, if the monitor is calibrated.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A picture that uses colors that are outside the sRGB color space will display on an sRGB color space monitor with limitations.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Still today, many monitors that can display the sRGB color space are not factory nor user-calibrated to display it correctly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Color management is needed both in electronic publishing (via the Internet for display in browsers) and in desktop publishing targeted to print.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Most modern monitors will switch to a power-saving mode if no video-input signal is received.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This allows modern operating systems to turn off a monitor after a specified period of inactivity.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This also extends the monitor's service life.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Some monitors will also switch themselves off after a time period on standby.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Most modern laptops provide a method of screen dimming after periods of inactivity or when the battery is in use.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This extends battery life and reduces wear.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Most modern monitors have two different indicator light colors wherein if video-input signal was detected, the indicator light is green and when the monitor is in power-saving mode, the screen is black and the indicator light is orange.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Some monitors have different indicator light colors and some monitors have a blinking indicator light when in power-saving mode.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Many monitors have other accessories (or connections for them) integrated.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This places standard ports within easy reach and eliminates the need for another separate hub, camera, microphone, or set of speakers.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] These monitors have advanced microprocessors which contain codec information, Windows interface drivers and other small software which help in proper functioning of these functions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Monitors that feature an aspect ratio greater than 2:1 (for instance, 21:9 or 32:9, as opposed to the more common 16:9, which resolves to 1.77:1).Monitors with an aspect ratio greater than 3:1 are marketed as super ultrawide monitors.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] These are typically massive curved screens intended to replace a multi-monitor deployment.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] These monitors use touching of the screen as an input method.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Items can be selected or moved with a finger, and finger gestures may be used to convey commands.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The screen will need frequent cleaning due to image degradation from fingerprints.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Some displays, especially newer flat-panel monitors, replace the traditional anti-glare matte finish with a glossy one.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This increases color saturation and sharpness but reflections from lights and windows are more visible.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Anti-reflective coatings are sometimes applied to help reduce reflections, although this only partly mitigates the problem.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Most often using nominally flat-panel display technology such as LCD or OLED, a concave rather than convex curve is imparted, reducing geometric distortion, especially in extremely large and wide seamless desktop monitors intended for close viewing range.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Newer monitors are able to display a different image for each eye, often with the help of special glasses and polarizers, giving the perception of depth.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] An autostereoscopic screen can generate 3D images without headgear.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Features for medical using or for outdoor placement.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Narrow viewing angle screens are used in some security-conscious applications.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Integrated screen calibration tools, screen hoods, signal transmitters; Protective screens.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A combination of a monitor with a graphics tablet.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Such devices are typically unresponsive to touch without the use of one or more special tools' pressure.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Newer models however are now able to detect touch from any pressure and often have the ability to detect tool tilt and rotation as well.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Touch and tablet sensors are often used on sample and hold displays such as LCDs to substitute for the light pen, which can only work on CRTs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The option for using the display as a reference monitor; these calibration features can give an advanced color management control for take a near-perfect image.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Option for professional LCD monitors, inherent to OLED & CRT; professional feature with mainstream tendency.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Near to mainstream professional feature; advanced hardware driver for backlit modules with local zones of uniformity correction.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Computer monitors are provided with a variety of methods for mounting them depending on the application and environment.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A desktop monitor is typically provided with a stand from the manufacturer which lifts the monitor up to a more ergonomic viewing height.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The stand may be attached to the monitor using a proprietary method or may use, or be adaptable to, a VESA mount.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A VESA standard mount allows the monitor to be used with more after-market stands if the original stand is removed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Stands may be fixed or offer a variety of features such as height adjustment, horizontal swivel, and landscape or portrait screen orientation.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The Flat Display Mounting Interface (FDMI), also known as VESA Mounting Interface Standard (MIS) or colloquially as a VESA mount, is a family of standards defined by the Video Electronics Standards Association for mounting flat-panel displays to stands or wall mounts.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] It is implemented on most modern flat-panel monitors and TVs.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] For computer monitors, the VESA Mount typically consists of four threaded holes on the rear of the display that will mate with an adapter bracket.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A fixed rack mount monitor is mounted directly to the rack with the flat-panel or CRT visible at all times.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The height of the unit is measured in rack units (RU) and 8U or 9U are most common to fit 17-inch or 19-inch screens.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The front sides of the unit are provided with flanges to mount to the rack, providing appropriately spaced holes or slots for the rack mounting screws.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A 19-inch diagonal screen is the largest size that will fit within the rails of a 19-inch rack.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Larger flat-panels may be accommodated but are 'mount-on-rack' and extend forward of the rack.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] There are smaller display units, typically used in broadcast environments, which fit multiple smaller screens side by side into one rack mount.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A stowable rack mount monitor is 1U, 2U or 3U high and is mounted on rack slides allowing the display to be folded down and the unit slid into the rack for storage as a drawer.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The flat display is visible only when pulled out of the rack and deployed.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] These units may include only a display or may be equipped with a keyboard creating a KVM (Keyboard Video Monitor).
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Most common are systems with a single LCD but there are systems providing two or three displays in a single rack mount system.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A panel mount computer monitor is intended for mounting into a flat surface with the front of the display unit protruding just slightly.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] They may also be mounted to the rear of the panel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] A flange is provided around the screen, sides, top and bottom, to allow mounting.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] This contrasts with a rack mount display where the flanges are only on the sides.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] The flanges will be provided with holes for thru-bolts or may have studs welded to the rear surface to secure the unit in the hole in the panel.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Often a gasket is provided to provide a water-tight seal to the panel and the front of the screen will be sealed to the back of the front panel to prevent water and dirt contamination.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] An open frame monitor provides the display and enough supporting structure to hold associated electronics and to minimally support the display.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Provision will be made for attaching the unit to some external structure for support and protection.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Open frame monitors are intended to be built into some other piece of equipment providing its own case.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] An arcade video game would be a good example with the display mounted inside the cabinet.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] There is usually an open frame display inside all end-use displays with the end-use display simply providing an attractive protective enclosure.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Some rack mount monitor manufacturers will purchase desktop displays, take them apart, and discard the outer plastic parts, keeping the inner open-frame display for inclusion into their product.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] According to a National Security Agency (NSA) document leaked to *Der Spiegel*, the NSA sometimes swaps the monitor cables on targeted computers with a bugged monitor cable to allow the NSA to remotely see what is being displayed on the targeted computer monitor.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Van Eck phreaking is the process of remotely displaying the contents of a CRT or LCD by detecting its electromagnetic emissions.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] It is named after Dutch computer researcher Wim van Eck, who in 1985 published the first paper on it, including proof of concept.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] While most effective on older CRT monitors due to their strong electromagnetic emissions, it can potentially apply to LCDs as well, although modern shielding techniques significantly mitigate the risk.
[src:3d-lookup-table/computer-monitor] Phreaking more generally is the process of exploiting telephone networks.
